description.value: Egyptian terracotta circular stamp. A circular bread-stamp(?), with an applied rectangular grip on the centre back. It has an incuse pattern: within a myrtle wreath, bound at the bottom, a victorious cockerel walks (in the impression) to right, with a palm branch held in a wing. A small victor’s wreath is part hidden by the branch, and a looped wreath of flowers is shown before the bird’s chest; below the tail is a large leaf or pine cone. Pressed over a plaster form. Traces of a red slip on the front. Brown-black (over fired) Nile silt with a red-brown surface, with fine gold mica and white grits.

description.value: Egyptian terracotta circular stamp. A circular bread-stamp (?), with applied elongated grip on the centre back. It has an incuse pattern: within a border of short radiating grooves enclosing a narrow wreath, is a bull’s head to front, with a fillet tied across its brow, and a dewlap indicated below the muzzle; a solar disc is shown between the horns: probably the Apis Bull, but other sacred bulls are possible. Made by pressing over a modelled form. Red-brown Nile silt, with abundant gold mica and white inclusions; the surface has fired buff, either salt-induced, or a slip.

description.value: Fragment of a terracotta stamp. A fragment of a large circular bread-stamp (?). There is no handle on the back, although the absolute centre does not survive. The pattern is largely incuse: within a band of egg-and-dart and one of bead-and-reel, moving to right (in the impression), part of a goat remains (the hooves are cloven and the body proportions do not seem correct for a bull); an uncertain object crosses the middle of the animal’s body, possibly a garland. Within a ground-line, in relief letters and retrograde in the stamp, is the name T?O??S (Theonos). Pressed over a plaster form. Orange-brown Nile silt, with a brown surface and abundant fine gold mica and white inclusions.
